  <mj-section background-color="#ffffff">
    <mj-column>
      <mj-spacer height="14px" />
          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">Doughing good </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">The linked prosperity model worked. By 1989, it had grown to $58 Mn. In 1991, it became the first publicly traded company to offer benefits to same-sex couples. <strong>The company adopted a 5-to-1 salary ratio</strong>, ensuring that the highest-paid employee could earn no more than five times the salary of the lowest-paid worker. It launched nonprofit initiatives like "<a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-08-03-2025-2-one-percent-for-peace" target="_blank">One Percent for Peace</a>" and created "Rock the Vote." 
         </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">The mid-1990s, however, were a challenging time for Ben & Jerry’s. The once-thriving company saw its financial performance decline, and by the second quarter of 1993, sales and income growth had slowed to just 4%. In August 1994, its <strong>annual report revealed its first financial loss</strong>. A growing sentiment within the company suggested that its strong social mission was a luxury it could no longer afford.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">As a publicly traded company, they had a fiduciary duty to consider the best financial interests of their shareholders. The board ultimately concluded that a takeover was inevitable. Neither Cohen nor Greenfield wanted to sell, but few options were available then. On April 11, 2000, after nearly two years of negotiations, <strong>Ben & Jerry’s board agreed to sell the company to Unilever</strong> for $326 million at $43.60 per share.</p>
          </mj-text>
          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">Frozen assets</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5"><strong>Ben & Jerry’s fought to preserve its legacy</strong> after the acquisition. Recognizing this, Unilever agreed to a unique sales agreement. Ben & Jerry’s would remain a wholly owned subsidiary with special rights, ensuring it retained a Vermont-based CEO and an independent board of directors. This board, which included Cohen and Greenfield, was given control over product quality, social initiatives, and the company’s trademark.</p>
          </mj-text>

          <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px 14px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/ben-jerrys-flavor-graveyard-vermont-discontinued-ice-cream-tombstones.png" alt="Ben & Jerry’s Flavor Graveyard in Vermont, a real-life cemetery honoring discontinued ice cream flavors with witty tombstones" href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />
           <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
            <i>
            Ben & Jerry’s Flavor Graveyard in Vermont is a real-life cemetery honoring discontinued ice cream flavors with witty tombstones. Credits: Ben & Jerry’s</i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>

          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">It wasn’t until 2011 that <strong>Vermont enacted its Benefit Corporation Act</strong>, a law designed to protect mission-driven companies. Commentators believe that if this law had existed a decade earlier, maybe Ben & Jerry’s would not have had to sell. The Benefit Corporation laws allow businesses to pursue social missions and maintain their independence through a legal framework, ensuring they are not overridden by shareholder profit primacy.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">Recently, <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-08-03-2025-3-ben-and-jerrys-sued-unilever" target="_blank">Ben and Jerry’s sued Unilever</a> for blocking it from speaking out against the humanitarian crisis in Gaza. Many are asking Unilever to divest the ice company. Despite being a once bitter ending for Cohen and Greenfield, in many ways, these laws protecting social entrepreneurs are like flowers that bloomed from the graves of companies like Ben & Jerry’s.</p>
          </mj-text> 
      </mj-column>
